1. Moniroing Cluster Components and logs
In the kuberenetes cluster, why monitor?
To retrive the number of nodes in the cluser and how many are healthy & performance metrics of the node such as CPU, Memory, Network and 
Disk utilization. We use Metrics-Server to retrive it.

Also, to retrive the number of pods in the node and  to check the performance metrics of the pods such as CPU, Memory of them.

Below are the tools use to anyalse the data and show the metrics in the easy way to view it.
Metric-Server
Prometheus
Elastic Stack
Dynatrace

# kubectl top node
# kubectl top pods

A. Deploy the Metrics Server in your Kubernetes cluster by applying the latest release components.yaml manifest using the following command:

Run the kubectl apply -f https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/metrics-server/releases/latest/download/components.yaml
kubectl apply -f https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/metrics-server/releases/latest/download/components.yaml
serviceaccount/metrics-server created
clusterrole.rbac.authorization.k8s.io/system:aggregated-metrics-reader created
clusterrole.rbac.authorization.k8s.io/system:metrics-server created
rolebinding.rbac.authorization.k8s.io/metrics-server-auth-reader created
clusterrolebinding.rbac.authorization.k8s.io/metrics-server:system:auth-delegator created
clusterrolebinding.rbac.authorization.k8s.io/system:metrics-server created
service/metrics-server created
deployment.apps/metrics-server created
apiservice.apiregistration.k8s.io/v1beta1.metrics.k8s.io create




2. Monitoring Applications and logs
If we run the application with detached mode, runs a container in the background.
# docker run -d <docker_image>

In the docker, we want to check the existing application logs from the container deployed
# docker logs event-simulator-app

-f to check the following logs live events of the application
# docker logs -f event-simulator-app

Similarly in the Kubernetes
# kubectl logs -f event-simulatora-app (will show the live logs of the application in the container)

But in the kuberentes we have mulitple containers in the pods.
# kubectl logs -f event-simulator-app -c container_name (mention the container name to show the logs of the application in the specific container)
















